Because the whole talk collapses if people say, whatever.

23
00:00:54,901 --> 00:00:55,821
So OK.

24
00:00:55,841 --> 00:00:57,883
So that's a very pernicious problem, very complicated,

25
00:00:57,903 --> 00:00:58,483
very systemic.

26
00:00:59,124 --> 00:01:02,246
And I am not going to offer you the solution.

27
00:01:02,266 --> 00:01:04,627
I'm not going to say, this is a silver bullet, those don't exist.

28
00:01:05,468 --> 00:01:08,230
But hopefully, I can cast a new light on this problem

29
00:01:08,270 --> 00:01:10,351
by showing you a design approach that I found extremely

30
00:01:10,411 --> 00:01:13,353
useful in game design, and that sort of is

31
00:01:13,414 --> 00:01:14,134
relevant to that problem.

32
00:01:14,875 --> 00:01:18,897
So I'm going to start with some quick definitions, some examples, then I'll talk about the design

33
00:01:18,917 --> 00:01:22,419
approach, and then I'm going to talk about what that means for storytelling in games.

34
00:01:23,940 --> 00:01:30,044
So first, I'd like to ask you to suspend your disbelief for the duration of this talk and

35
00:01:30,084 --> 00:01:34,107
to accept two simple, non-academic definitions of terms that I'm going to be using during

36
00:01:34,127 --> 00:01:37,449
this talk, just for the sake of argument, because terminology in storytelling in games

37
00:01:37,489 --> 00:01:40,110
I found to be a very complicated issue.

38
00:01:40,751 --> 00:01:40,851
So...

39
00:01:42,142 --> 00:01:43,863
When I talk about story, I talk about this.

40
00:01:43,903 --> 00:01:45,525
I talk about something that was pre-offered,

41
00:01:45,885 --> 00:01:47,366
and it's about something happening to someone.

42
00:01:47,386 --> 00:01:49,347
Because people get confused by what

43
00:01:49,367 --> 00:01:51,329
is meant by story in games, including me.

44
00:01:51,509 --> 00:01:54,170
And so I mean pre-offered story.

45
00:01:54,190 --> 00:01:55,591
I don't mean an emergent story.

46
00:01:55,651 --> 00:01:56,852
I don't mean the story that you're

47
00:01:56,872 --> 00:01:58,453
telling me about the game you played last night.

48
00:01:58,513 --> 00:02:00,615
I don't mean the story as it's happening while you're playing.

49
00:02:01,015 --> 00:02:02,096
I don't mean back story.

50
00:02:02,176 --> 00:02:03,137
I mean this.

51
00:02:04,077 --> 00:02:08,220
And so fictional, I'm going to talk about this a lot.

52
00:02:08,260 --> 00:02:10,201
This is an important concept for this talk.

53
00:02:11,142 --> 00:02:12,703
This is about willing suspension of disbelief,

54
00:02:12,723 --> 00:02:15,225
so fictional means related to things I'm asking you

55
00:02:15,245 --> 00:02:16,226
to pretend are true, right?

56
00:02:16,246 --> 00:02:19,188
So I am, as designers, as game creators,

57
00:02:19,268 --> 00:02:22,030
we are asking people to believe that this bunch of pixels

58
00:02:22,130 --> 00:02:24,632
is a plumber and that's a barrel and that's a monkey, right?

59
00:02:24,852 --> 00:02:27,254
And that's kind of a core.

60
00:02:29,235 --> 00:02:32,377
Okay, so an example.

61
00:02:34,098 --> 00:02:35,980
Let's say you have a game where you have hit points, right?

62
00:02:36,140 --> 00:02:39,242
So we've been using hit points as a mechanic for decades.

63
00:02:41,970 --> 00:02:42,571
Works very well.

64
00:02:43,211 --> 00:02:44,833
It means that if the player hits an enemy,

65
00:02:44,873 --> 00:02:46,014
she's not killed instantly.

66
00:02:46,034 --> 00:02:47,415
You can sort of take that away a little bit.

67
00:02:47,935 --> 00:02:48,456
So hit points.

68
00:02:48,536 --> 00:02:48,696
OK.

69
00:02:49,237 --> 00:02:50,758
So you need to show the player how many hit points

70
00:02:50,778 --> 00:02:51,578
she has left, right?

71
00:02:51,599 --> 00:02:53,240
Because otherwise, you don't get the right dynamic going.

72
00:02:54,181 --> 00:02:55,121
Very common design problem.

73
00:02:55,141 --> 00:02:55,822
So how do you do that?

74
00:02:56,483 --> 00:02:59,926
Well, the easy solution is what Doom does

75
00:02:59,966 --> 00:03:01,587
and what billions of games have done,

76
00:03:01,627 --> 00:03:03,529
is just put the number on the screen, right?

77
00:03:03,869 --> 00:03:05,550
There it is, very clear.

78
00:03:06,111 --> 00:03:07,032
People know what's going on.

79
00:03:07,832 --> 00:03:08,513
Works great.

80
00:03:09,564 --> 00:03:12,926
Now let's say that you say you want to really immerse

81
00:03:12,966 --> 00:03:13,726
the player in the world.

82
00:03:13,786 --> 00:03:15,767
You don't want any gamey numbers on the screen

83
00:03:15,787 --> 00:03:18,068
because you think that breaks suspension of disbelief, right?

84
00:03:18,988 --> 00:03:19,528
So what do you do?

85
00:03:19,628 --> 00:03:22,109
Well, if you're Valve and Half-Life,

86
00:03:22,490 --> 00:03:23,190
working in Half-Life,

87
00:03:24,010 --> 00:03:26,431
you find an explanation in your game setting, right?

88
00:03:26,591 --> 00:03:29,212
You say, well, you know, this is slightly sort of sci-fi game

89
00:03:29,272 --> 00:03:32,214
so what if the player character puts on this sort of

90
00:03:32,234 --> 00:03:34,615
high-tech exosuit that has an actual heads-up display

91
00:03:34,655 --> 00:03:36,155
and then we can show all the different numbers

92
00:03:36,175 --> 00:03:37,616
that are important for gameplay right there?

93
00:03:38,436 --> 00:03:43,098
Even though, you know, why an industrial exosuit would show the amount of bullets you have left in your gun,

94
00:03:43,138 --> 00:03:45,919
you know, like, doesn't really make sense. But, you know, it's good enough, right?

95
00:03:46,239 --> 00:03:51,081
So, beautiful solution, makes total sense, or, well, almost total sense, in the world of the game.

96
00:03:52,161 --> 00:03:54,662
But now, let's say you love this idea of not having numbers on screen,

97
00:03:54,822 --> 00:04:01,664
but your game has a fantasy setting and, you know, you don't want to try and come up with a fantasy exosuit, right?

98
00:04:01,704 --> 00:04:02,585
So what do you do?

99
00:04:03,485 --> 00:04:07,447
Well, if you're Team Ico, you take out hit points all together, right?

100
00:04:07,864 --> 00:04:09,926
You think about, well, why do we even need hit points?

101
00:04:09,986 --> 00:04:12,529
What are the dynamics we're trying to generate?

102
00:04:13,250 --> 00:04:16,333
Why do we need, why do we want the player to know about them?

103
00:04:16,774 --> 00:04:19,197
And so instead, you make all the situations in the game

104
00:04:19,277 --> 00:04:21,039
very clearly deadly or not, right?

105
00:04:21,619 --> 00:04:23,742
In ICO, I find it sort of cool, it's like,

106
00:04:24,623 --> 00:04:27,085
if it looks like a kid would die falling from that height,

107
00:04:28,060 --> 00:04:29,140
he'll probably die, right?

108
00:04:29,981 --> 00:04:30,981
It's very obvious, right?

109
00:04:31,001 --> 00:04:31,781
You don't need to think about it.

110
00:04:31,801 --> 00:04:32,642
There's nothing to explain.

111
00:04:32,682 --> 00:04:33,182
It's very clear.

112
00:04:33,522 --> 00:04:35,103
And then, you know, the enemies, they

113
00:04:35,143 --> 00:04:37,384
don't actually harm the player character.

114
00:04:37,404 --> 00:04:39,985
They just slow him down while his companion, Princess Yorda,

115
00:04:40,005 --> 00:04:41,945
is being dragged off into the void.

116
00:04:42,306 --> 00:04:43,326
And then the game ends, right?

117
00:04:43,626 --> 00:04:46,747
So they have this kind of delay mechanic in there.

118
00:04:46,767 --> 00:04:49,589
And they have kind of the same dynamic and effects

119
00:04:49,849 --> 00:04:50,449
as for midpoints.

120
00:04:51,503 --> 00:04:53,384
in a different way and without requiring

121
00:04:53,565 --> 00:04:54,465
any numbers on screen.

122
00:04:54,645 --> 00:04:55,906
And I think it's great.

123
00:04:56,087 --> 00:04:56,947
It's also a lot of work,

124
00:04:56,987 --> 00:04:58,248
because they have to reinvent all this stuff.

125
00:04:58,268 --> 00:04:59,850
You know, it's like, oh, let's get the off-the-shelf

126
00:05:00,010 --> 00:05:00,710
hit point module.

127
00:05:02,051 --> 00:05:03,152
And it affects the whole game.

128
00:05:03,192 --> 00:05:04,754
There are certain things they cannot easily

129
00:05:05,014 --> 00:05:07,156
put in their game by using this.

130
00:05:07,196 --> 00:05:08,457
But, you know, it's a wonderful solution.

131
00:05:10,658 --> 00:05:12,020
So what do we just see here?

132
00:05:16,343 --> 00:05:18,325
We were looking at sort of two sides of the game,

133
00:05:18,725 --> 00:05:21,027
the mechanical side, which is the rule side,

134
00:05:21,127 --> 00:05:23,189
and then the fictional side, right?

135
00:05:23,669 --> 00:05:25,391
And I find it an incredibly useful way

136
00:05:25,431 --> 00:05:26,572
of looking at game design,

137
00:05:26,612 --> 00:05:29,995
and I've been using this approach a lot.

138
00:05:30,836 --> 00:05:32,197
since quite a long time.

139
00:05:32,517 --> 00:05:33,798
I know other game designers have too,

140
00:05:33,858 --> 00:05:35,019
it's not something particularly new,

141
00:05:35,059 --> 00:05:37,181
but you know, and they may not use these exact words.

142
00:05:37,541 --> 00:05:38,742
But it's very, very useful.

143
00:05:38,762 --> 00:05:40,523
And you look at your games from these two sides,

144
00:05:40,884 --> 00:05:42,125
you try to make things come together

145
00:05:42,145 --> 00:05:43,746
into one sort of pleasing experience,

146
00:05:44,587 --> 00:05:45,888
the experience that you want to achieve.

147
00:05:46,508 --> 00:05:48,189
Because if you don't balance those two sides,

148
00:05:48,690 --> 00:05:51,011
you get dissonance, or you can get dissonance,

149
00:05:51,071 --> 00:05:52,112
which you usually don't want,

150
00:05:52,332 --> 00:05:55,255
and you risk breaking the player suspension of this way.

151
00:05:57,967 --> 00:06:01,089
The mechanical side of a game is really abstract, right?

152
00:06:02,050 --> 00:06:03,971
It's the fiction that gives the game meaning.

153
00:06:04,731 --> 00:06:05,872
And of course, the mechanical side

154
00:06:05,892 --> 00:06:07,173
has a big effect on the experience,

155
00:06:07,213 --> 00:06:08,694
because otherwise, why do it?

156
00:06:08,754 --> 00:06:10,575
And also, they're games.

157
00:06:11,275 --> 00:06:13,917
But if I just say, when this counter hits zero,

158
00:06:13,957 --> 00:06:16,098
the game ends, that can sort of mean anything.

159
00:06:16,138 --> 00:06:18,240
That is very cold, very abstract, right?

160
00:06:19,300 --> 00:06:22,542
And so the fictional side is what we're asking,

161
00:06:22,823 --> 00:06:25,064
like I said earlier, what we're asking players to believe when

162
00:06:25,084 --> 00:06:26,345
we talk about suspension of disbelief.

163
00:06:27,380 --> 00:06:30,862
And every design element can be seen from the mechanical and from the fictional side.

164
00:06:31,422 --> 00:06:35,184
And it's important to realize that these are two sides of the same thing, right?

165
00:06:35,564 --> 00:06:36,345
They're not separate.

166
00:06:36,385 --> 00:06:39,807
They're aspects or dimensions or perspectives on one thing.

167
00:06:42,268 --> 00:06:42,428
Right.

168
00:06:42,648 --> 00:06:48,811
So to balance the fictional and the mechanical often involves explaining a mechanical element

169
00:06:48,931 --> 00:06:50,632
and justifying it within the game setting.

170
00:06:51,650 --> 00:06:54,251
And the sort of fancy word for this is diegesis,

171
00:06:54,871 --> 00:06:56,672
which is a word that, the way I use it,

172
00:06:56,752 --> 00:06:57,892
comes from sound design.

173
00:06:58,052 --> 00:07:01,134
You know, if you watch a movie and you see a radio

174
00:07:01,154 --> 00:07:02,594
and the radio's playing music,

175
00:07:02,795 --> 00:07:04,655
and the characters in the movie can't hear that music,

176
00:07:04,855 --> 00:07:06,036
that is called diegetic music.

177
00:07:06,716 --> 00:07:07,617
And if you have like, you know,

178
00:07:07,637 --> 00:07:10,418
like the typical Hollywood score that you can hear,

179
00:07:10,458 --> 00:07:13,119
but the characters cannot unless they break the fourth wall,

180
00:07:13,819 --> 00:07:15,520
that is called non-diegetic music, right?

181
00:07:15,580 --> 00:07:18,321
And it's a very simple concept that's used in sound design,

182
00:07:18,361 --> 00:07:20,682
but I also find it very useful for game design.

183
00:07:22,646 --> 00:07:24,506
And what you do when you explain the mechanical,

184
00:07:24,546 --> 00:07:28,607
when you make things diegetic, is really world building.

185
00:07:29,327 --> 00:07:30,927
You're inventing how the world works.

186
00:07:31,588 --> 00:07:33,488
You're inventing which creatures and characters

187
00:07:33,548 --> 00:07:35,388
exist in the game, why they behave a certain way,

188
00:07:35,428 --> 00:07:36,348
why they act a certain way.

189
00:07:37,809 --> 00:07:40,669
So I wanna just show two more examples.

190
00:07:44,790 --> 00:07:47,010
Actually three, just to show a couple of things

191
00:07:47,030 --> 00:07:49,431
that you can make diegetic, that you can sort of explain

192
00:07:49,491 --> 00:07:51,031
and justify inside your setting.

193
00:07:53,388 --> 00:07:57,711
So character death is a convention of video games

194
00:07:57,771 --> 00:07:59,773
and has been around for decades, right?

195
00:07:59,853 --> 00:08:01,594
Your guy dies and you have to start all over again.

196
00:08:02,635 --> 00:08:06,037
But actually it is harmful to suspension of disbelief.

197
00:08:06,137 --> 00:08:08,559
And so various games over time have tried to sort of explain

198
00:08:08,599 --> 00:08:09,239
it and integrate it.

199
00:08:09,860 --> 00:08:11,941
And one solution that I find really cool

200
00:08:12,122 --> 00:08:14,303
is the one they used in Prince of Persia, Sense of Time,

201
00:08:14,964 --> 00:08:18,186
where the entire game has this framing story of like

202
00:08:18,660 --> 00:08:20,641
the main character narrating his adventures,

203
00:08:21,261 --> 00:08:24,742
which fits really well with the whole Arabian Nights setting.

204
00:08:25,702 --> 00:08:28,443
And when you do die in the game, the character goes like,

205
00:08:28,463 --> 00:08:29,583
no, no, no, no, that's not what happened.

206
00:08:29,743 --> 00:08:32,984
And sort of goes back a little way and tells it again.

207
00:08:33,004 --> 00:08:35,484
And I find it a really cool solution.

208
00:08:37,265 --> 00:08:39,365
Now, another convention of video games that

209
00:08:40,911 --> 00:08:42,172
we don't really think about a lot,

210
00:08:42,252 --> 00:08:45,153
is that there are these levels, these situations,

211
00:08:45,454 --> 00:08:46,874
which have been created for the player

212
00:08:46,954 --> 00:08:50,296
to challenge the player and to test them.

213
00:08:50,677 --> 00:08:52,898
And it's like, why?

214
00:08:53,358 --> 00:08:53,858
Who does that?

215
00:08:54,499 --> 00:08:55,599
The question I used to ask a lot

216
00:08:55,619 --> 00:08:57,380
when I was doing role-playing games in the 90s was like,

217
00:08:57,721 --> 00:08:58,821
well, who built this dungeon?

218
00:08:59,001 --> 00:09:00,963
And why does it still work after thousands of years, right?

219
00:09:01,483 --> 00:09:04,565
And, you know, it's a convention,

220
00:09:04,605 --> 00:09:06,806
and you don't think about it that much, but it's there.

221
00:09:06,846 --> 00:09:08,367
And so one game which has sort of,

222
00:09:10,135 --> 00:09:15,537
explain that is Portal. And I think it's probably the most brilliant thing about Portal to me.

223
00:09:16,478 --> 00:09:21,299
They have explained why these levels are there, and they have explained it in a completely unique

224
00:09:21,339 --> 00:09:25,881
way, and they've even given a... they have put the level designer, in a way, the game designer,

225
00:09:26,001 --> 00:09:28,542
as a character into the game, right, as GLaDOS.

226
00:09:29,445 --> 00:09:30,426
And I think that's brilliant.

227
00:09:31,206 --> 00:09:33,826
Another game which does the same thing is Manhunt,

228
00:09:33,906 --> 00:09:37,527
where in the game, a very, I must stress this,

229
00:09:37,867 --> 00:09:39,808
in the game, a very sick and disturbed individual

230
00:09:39,868 --> 00:09:43,589
has created all these levels in a decrepit part of town

231
00:09:43,629 --> 00:09:45,529
and is forcing your character to go through

232
00:09:45,569 --> 00:09:48,710
and kill, I'm not gonna say innocent people,

233
00:09:48,730 --> 00:09:51,511
but kill people for his amusement

234
00:09:51,551 --> 00:09:53,431
while literally whispering in your ear, right?

235
00:09:54,091 --> 00:09:56,932
And that makes Manhunt a very special experience.

236
00:09:59,495 --> 00:10:06,418
So what happens when I use this approach in the design process?

237
00:10:06,798 --> 00:10:08,979
I tend to go back and forth between the mechanical

238
00:10:08,999 --> 00:10:10,140
and the fictional.

239
00:10:10,680 --> 00:10:12,961
You find some explanations for mechanical elements.

240
00:10:13,582 --> 00:10:15,803
And once you've done that, that may trigger new ideas

241
00:10:15,943 --> 00:10:16,703
for the mechanical side.

242
00:10:16,723 --> 00:10:18,504
Because you go like, OK, so we've

243
00:10:18,644 --> 00:10:20,905
added this to the world so that this makes sense.

244
00:10:20,965 --> 00:10:22,966
And then like, hey, but that means that blah.

245
00:10:23,026 --> 00:10:24,587
And then, ah, that means these new mechanics.

246
00:10:24,627 --> 00:10:25,268
This is super cool.

247
00:10:25,748 --> 00:10:28,089
And it's not uncommon to go back and forth a couple of times.

248
00:10:29,751 --> 00:10:34,874
And here's an example from, this is a screenshot from Deus Ex Invisible War.

249
00:10:36,675 --> 00:10:42,699
In Deus Ex 1 and Deus Ex sequel, you have these biomods, right, these augmentations

250
00:10:42,760 --> 00:10:46,182
that you can sort of slot into your body and they give you new powers, right?

251
00:10:46,722 --> 00:10:50,805
